254
00:13:34,671 --> 00:13:41,610
Rym: So, unless you have a very strong regional accent that you also hear, you'll eventually drift toward this common one, like generation over generation.

255
00:13:42,434 --> 00:14:07,510
Rym: The internet is interesting in that communities of people are continuously sharing podcasts and YouTube videos and Let's Plays, and this article talks about what the YouTube accent looks like, and it's kind of fascinating, because Scott and I both do a lot of these things, as do most of our podcaster friends, almost every Let's Play person I've ever seen who's popular, and actually Crash Course, all those guys.

256
00:14:07,610 --> 00:14:11,889
Rym: They do this so close to the way it's described that it's uncanny.

257
00:14:13,171 --> 00:14:14,590
Rym: So, I'd recommend you read this.

258
00:14:14,690 --> 00:14:24,369
Rym: I mean, this is what it comes down to, and you can read the article, look at all the details, there's a bunch of follow-up stories and everything, but the components are, one, over-stressed vowels.

259
00:14:25,231 --> 00:14:32,650
Rym: So, like, instead of making a schwa, you'll say the syllables, and the vowel syllables, at least, very strongly in words you say.

260
00:14:32,710 --> 00:14:34,470
Rym: You won't kind of "eh" the syllables.

261
00:14:34,770 --> 00:14:37,790
Rym: Like, exactly, instead of exactly, or exactly.

262
00:14:38,310 --> 00:14:40,369
Rym: Like, you'll stress all those bits along the way.

263
00:14:41,310 --> 00:14:44,449
Rym: Sneaking extra vowels in between consonants.

264
00:14:45,110 --> 00:14:51,670
Rym: So, instead of trapping, they'll actually, you'll hear the sort of terrapping, you'll hear this "eh" coming in, like splitting up the bits.

265
00:14:52,611 --> 00:14:56,248
Rym: There's technical terms for all this, but I don't know shit about linguistics, so I'm not even going to try.

266
00:14:57,170 --> 00:15:04,689
Rym: A lot more long vowels, long consonants as well, and actually, lots of aspiration and plosives.

267
00:15:05,330 --> 00:15:10,529
Rym: So, people who need pop filters tend to be the kinds of people who do this accent by default.

268
00:15:12,395 --> 00:15:22,687
Rym: And it's interesting, because the accent, it was described variously as intellectual used car salesman voice, or educated carnival barker.

269
00:15:24,513 --> 00:15:33,268
