00:30:42,521 --> 00:30:43,069
Rym: I really like it.

550
00:30:43,230 --> 00:30:45,249
Rym: And I kind of got good at it the more I played it.

551
00:30:45,770 --> 00:30:48,730
Scott: Yeah, I mean, it's clearly a game where you can get good at it.

552
00:30:48,790 --> 00:30:50,107
Scott: There is some skill going on.

553
00:30:50,591 --> 00:31:10,929
Scott: But it's like the skill ramp was like... It seemed like the skill ramp wasn't a bad ramp, poorly shaped, but it said like the first bunch of steps were not steps of learning skills, but instead dealing with controls that are intentionally bad or... I actually don't think... Some combination of intentionally and accidentally bad.

554
00:31:11,210 --> 00:31:12,870
Rym: It's interesting because I actually don't think they're bad.

555
00:31:12,990 --> 00:31:14,190
Rym: I think they're very intuitive.

556
00:31:14,670 --> 00:31:17,936
Rym: What I noticed was people who kept asking like, "How do I turn?

557
00:31:17,996 --> 00:31:18,500
Rym: How do I move?

558
00:31:18,520 --> 00:31:18,782
Rym: How do I

559
00:31:18,823 --> 00:31:19,125
Rym: whatever?".

560
00:31:19,891 --> 00:31:22,890
Rym: Couldn't understand the game and wanted someone to explain how to move.

561
00:31:22,930 --> 00:31:25,530
Scott: It's asteroids controls, but they're wobbly and limited.

562
00:31:25,930 --> 00:31:28,609
Rym: Well, what it is, is that you can kind of direct your narwhal.

563
00:31:29,211 --> 00:31:30,030
Rym: Star wall, I guess.

564
00:31:30,711 --> 00:31:32,550
Rym: And you can hold A to kind of accelerate.

565
00:31:33,191 --> 00:31:35,310
Rym: And if you wiggle your body right, you can kind of go faster.

566
00:31:35,931 --> 00:31:41,050
Rym: You've just got your sword point on the end of your narwhal, and you're trying to stab the other narwhals in the heart.

567
00:31:41,490 --> 00:31:43,530
Scott: Right, so I didn't realize the heart part right away.

568
00:31:44,010 --> 00:31:45,521
Scott: We didn't like study the rule.

569
00:31:45,541 --> 00:31:46,770
Scott: We just started playing immediately.

570
00:31:47,353 --> 00:31:49,410
Scott: And I thought I just had to stab other narwhals.

571
00:31:49,410 --> 00:31:51,210
Scott: I didn't realize there was this heart I had to stab.

572
00:31:51,510 --> 00:31:54,210
Rym: I've noticed a lot of people who are bad at laser tag have the same problem.

573
00:31:54,330 --> 00:31:59,389
Rym: They think, because they don't know how anything works in the world, that you just shoot the other person.

574
00:32:00,072 --> 00:32:02,650
Rym: Like, they don't realize you have to shoot that one spot on their body pack.

575
00:32:02,910 --> 00:32:04,690
Scott: That actually can detect that they got shot, yeah.

576
00:32:05,210 --> 00:32:07,670
Scott: Right, but this, it wasn't that I, you know, was too dumb.

577
00:32:07,730 --> 00:32:08,645
Scott: It's just I didn't see it.

578
00:32:09,470 --> 00:32:11,586
Scott: And I just lost, and I'm like, "Why did I

579
00:32:11,647 --> 00:32:11,908
Scott: lose?".

580
00:32:12,191 --> 00:32:13,790
Rym: That's kind of an aside, because I noticed something.

581
00:32:13,890 --> 00:32:23,130
Rym: The games where you had to look at the controls and like really think about them, or you could not play at all, tended to be the worst of the games we tried on Steam.

582
00:32:23,910 --> 00:32:28,350
Rym: And the games like this where, like, you could pretty much play it okay by looking at zero rules.

583
00:32:28,370 --> 00:32:32,021
Scott: I mean, as soon as someone told me about the heart, I was like, "Oh, okay, I didn't need any more rules

584
00:32:32,102 --> 00:32:32,807
Scott: explanations.".

585
00:32:33,556 --> 00:32:34,610
Scott: Yeah, the rest was intuitive.

586
00:32:35,070 --> 00:32:44,489
Rym: I mean, basically, you fly around, and it's all around using the physics and dueling and trying to, like, maneuver yourself to where you can hit the narwhal in their heart without getting hit yourself.

587
00:32:44,570 --> 00:32:45,930
Scott: With your narwhal pointy-toothed.

588
00:32:45,990 --> 00:32:53,710
Rym: Yeah, which is extra interesting because your heart's only on one side of your body and you're playing in a two-dimensional space where you can kind of rotate freely.

589
00:32:54,150 --> 00:32:54,271
Scott: Right.

590
00:32:54,291 --> 00:33:04,310
Scott: Now, the one thing that I found out as we played that was kind of annoying is that when you start the game, your narwhal is facing either to the left or to the right, depending on your spawn location.

591
00:33:04,871 --> 00:33:08,447
Scott: And you can never flip your narwhal to face the other way ever.

592
00:33:09,531 --> 00:33:10,789
Rym: Which I think is fine.

593
00:33:11,491 --> 00:33:14,090
Scott: Well, I mean, it's not necessarily good or bad.

594
00:33:14,090 --> 00:33:16,250
Rym: The game is a four-player or a two-player game.

595
00:33:16,370 --> 00:33:17,250
Rym: Never play this three-player.

596
00:33:17,510 --> 00:33:21,450
Scott: If you play with three players, you'll have two, perhaps left-facing narwhals and one right-facing one.

597
00:33:21,470 --> 00:33:27,370
Rym: But as we've talked about in the past, three-player competitive games that are not races are usually bullshit.

598
00:33:27,650 --> 00:33:27,808
Rym: Right.

599
00:33:27,930 --> 00:33:29,510
Rym: And this would have that same problem.

600
00:33:29,870 --> 00:33:29,991
Scott: Right.

601
00:33:30,032 --> 00:33:34,850
Scott: But, I mean, so if it's two-on-two, though, but then you've got these different, you've got, like, three different ending situations, right?

602
00:33:34,911 --> 00:33:39,650
Scott: You've got the lefty-lefty, the righty-righty, and the mixed, you know, final confrontation between two narwhals.

603
00:33:39,650 --> 00:33:50,710
Rym: But it also means... It also means that two of the narwhals favor one area of the board and two of the narwhals favor another area of the board.

604
00:33:50,710 --> 00:33:50,811
Rym: Right.

605
00:33:50,831 --> 00:33:54,770
Scott: Now, the reason for this, if your narwhal was symmetrical, then it wouldn't matter.

606
00:33:54,850 --> 00:34:08,250
Scott: But your heart is on the bottom of your narwhal, which means if you flip, if you're a right-facing narwhal, that means, so you're facing to the right, you can hit people to the right, and your heart is on the ground, because there's gravity on most of the maps.

607
00:34:08,409 --> 00:34:08,510
Rym: Yeah.

608
00:34:08,850 --> 00:34:12,270
Scott: I mean, just relatively, that's a protected position when you're facing to the right.

609
00:34:12,672 --> 00:34:19,370
Scott: If you flip over because you want to stab someone to your left, then, suddenly, your heart is facing up and is exposed.

610
00:34:20,251 --> 00:34:23,029
Scott: So, that's why there's a righty-lefty thing going on.

611
00:34:23,870 --> 00:34:24,031
Rym: Yup.

612
00:34:24,393 --> 00:34:30,327
Rym: But the thing is, you can't, well, one, I would say, I'd give strategy or talk about, like, "Oh, well, you can't just lay there because then you won't

613
00:34:30,469 --> 00:34:30,549
Rym: win.".

614
00:34:30,610 --> 00:34:31,882
Scott: Obviously, you can't just lay there.

615
00:34:31,902 --> 00:34:32,590
Scott: It'd be really dumb.

616
00:34:32,750 --> 00:34:34,989
Rym: But, the game does something very well.

617
00:34:35,090 --> 00:34:41,150
Rym: It has the old Atari Ortho game thing, where there are a million different modes.

618
00:34:41,210 --> 00:34:41,565
Rym: Yup.

619
00:34:41,871 --> 00:34:43,130
Rym: And some of them are better than others.

620
00:34:43,250 --> 00:34:43,810
Scott: And the maps are different.

621
